'''Cecily Legler Strong''' (born February 8, 1984)<ref name="sjr1">{{cite web|url=http://www.sj-r.com/top-stories/x1665863890/New-SNL-comedian-has-shallow-Springfield-roots|title=New SNL Comedian has shallow Springfield roots|work=[[The State Journal-Register]]|location=Springfield, Illinois|first=Chris|last=Dettro|accessdate=October 5, 2013|date=January 19, 2013|quote=Strong's father, Bill Strong, was the Associated Press bureau chief at the Statehouse when Cecily was born in February 1984.|archivedate=November 3, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103123230/http://www.sj-r.com/x1665863890/New-SNL-comedian-has-shallow-Springfield-roots|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/nbcsnl/status/299955455151718400|title=Happy Birthday Cecily Strong!!|publisher=''Saturday Night Live'' official [[Twitter]] page|date=February 8, 2013|accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> is an American actress and comedian who has been a cast member of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' since 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Metz|first=Nina|title=Aidy Bryant, Tim Robinson, Cecily Strong join cast of 'SNL'|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-10/entertainment/chi-join-cast-on-snl-20120910_1_snl-executive-producer-weekend-update-io-theater|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref>
==Early life== Strong was born in [[Springfield, Illinois]], and was raised in [[Oak Park, Illinois]], an inner ring suburb of [[Chicago]].<ref name=sjr2>{{cite web|url=http://www.sj-r.com/entertainment/x1837085501/Cecily-Strong-to-co-anchor-SNLs-Weekend-Update|title=Cecily Strong to co-anchor SNL's 'Weekend Update'|publisher=Sj-r.com|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=October 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=October 2013}}</ref> She is the daughter of Penelope and William "Bill" Strong, who worked as an [[Associated Press]] bureau chief and is now managing partner at a Chicago [[public relations]] firm.<ref name="sjr1"/><ref name=sjr2/> Strong's parents are divorced.<ref name=trib/> Strong grew up adoring ''SNL'' as a child, reenacting sketches with her friend<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/magazine/cecily-strong-is-being-serious.html|title=Cecily Strong Is Being Serious|work=The New York Times|date=February 7, 2014|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> and watching old ''SNL'' commercials on VHS. "I had a tape of the best commercials, and I wore it out, every day." She has stated that she was inspired by [[Phil Hartman]].<ref>{{Cite video |url=https://vimeo.com/210965557 |title=Cecily Strong - Late Night with Jimmy Fallon (2013) |date=February 19, 2013}}</ref>
She attended [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]] before transferring for her senior year to the [[Chicago Academy for the Arts]], where she graduated in 2002.<ref name=trib/> She then studied acting at [[California Institute of the Arts]] (CalArts), graduating in 2006 with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] in theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scvnews.com/2012/12/11/calarts-grad-cecily-strong-joins-cast-of-snl/|title=CalArts Grad Cecily Strong Added to Cast of 'SNL'|date=December 11, 2012|publisher=SCV News|accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=NBC>{{cite web|title=Cast Bios|url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/bios/cecily-strong_38.shtml|work=Cecily Strong|publisher=NBC|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/snl-weekend-update-cecily-strong-1073130.aspx|title=Meet Saturday Night Live's New "Weekend Update" Anchor Cecily Strong|work=TV Guide|date=November 8, 2013|first=Bruce|last=Fretts|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> After graduating from [[CalArts]], Strong returned to Chicago, where she studied at the [[The Second City Training Center|Second City Conservatory]] and [[iO Theater|iO Chicago]].
==Career== Strong performed regularly at [[The Second City]] and [[IO Theater|iO Chicago]].<ref name=trib>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-06-14/entertainment/chi-interview-cecily-strong-20130613_1_box-office-second-city-aidy-bryant|title=Interview: 'SNL' star Cecily Strong returns home amid dream year|work=Chicago Tribune|date=June 14, 2013|first=Luis|last=Gomez|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Strong has performed on a "cruise ship with fellow Second City members for four months".<ref>http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/01/cecily-strong-saturday-night-live</ref> She appeared at the [[Chicago Sketch Fest]], [[Just for Laughs|Chicago Just for Laughs]], New York Sketchfest, the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]],<ref name=NBC/> at the [[Goodman Theater]], [[Bailiwick Repertory Theatre|Bailiwick Theater]], the Mercury Theater, and with the all-female improv troupe Virgin Daiquiri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cecilystrong.tumblr.com/|title=Cecily Strong|publisher=Tumblr|accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref>
===''Saturday Night Live''=== Strong debuted as a featured player on ''Saturday Night Live'' on September 15, 2012.<ref name=NBC/><ref>{{cite news|last=Levin|first=Gary|title='Saturday Night Live' adds three new cast members|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2012/09/Saturday-Night-Live-adds-three-new-cast-members-70000041/snl-adds-three-new-cast-members/70000041/1|newspaper=USA Today|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Saturday Night Live' adds 3 performers for upcoming season after departures of Wiig, Samberg|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/saturday-night-live-adds-3-performers-for-upcoming-season-after-departures-of-wiig-samberg/2012/09/10/e1bc7170-fb5f-11e1-98c6-ec0a0a93f8eb_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post (The Associated Press)|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Strong co-anchored the recurring ''[[Weekend Update]]'' segment with [[Seth Meyers]], beginning with the season 39 premiere. Strong later co-anchored with [[Colin Jost]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304279904579518191375460658|title=Cecily Strong and Colin Jost Are Newest 'Weekend Update' Anchors on 'Saturday Night Live'|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=May 9, 2014|first=Richard|last=Morgan|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> and was replaced on ''Weekend Update'' with writer [[Michael Che]], beginning with the season 40 premiere in September 2014, partly at her own request to focus on doing sketches as a part of the regular cast.<ref>Reed, Ryan (September 12, 2014). [https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/snl-replaces-cecily-strong-as-weekend-update-anchor-20140912 "'SNL' Replaces Cecily Strong as 'Weekend Update' Anchor"]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref>
Strong's recurring characters include an extremely ditzy, unintelligent and unnamed pseudo-activist known as "The Girl You Wish You Hadn't Started a Conversation With at a Party",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/March-2013/Questions-for-Saturday-Night-Lives-Cecily-Strong/|title=Questions for Saturday Night Live's Cecily Strong|work=Chicago Magazine|date=February 20, 2013|first=Elly|last=Fishman|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Dana (one of a pair of loud-mouthed, unfriendly retail employees who always insult their coworkers out of fear of being fired), Heather the One-Dimensional Female Character from a Male-Driven Comedy, Kyra from "The Girlfriends Talk Show", Cathy Anne, the drug addict neighbor of Michael Che, who has a strong opinion on current events, and an unnamed blond former porn star-turned-model/commercial actress who hawks elegant items. Most of her recurring characters are either very feminine, polished, youthful and/or mentally unstable. Her celebrity impressions include [[Huma Abedin]], [[Brooke Baldwin]], [[Maria Bartiromo]], [[Gloria Borger]], [[Paula Broadwell]], [[Erin Burnett]], [[Marion Cotillard]], [[Stormy Daniels]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[Fran Drescher]], [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Dianne Feinstein]], [[Carly Fiorina]], [[Ariana Grande]], [[Hope Hicks]], [[Scottie Nell Hughes]], [[Anjelica Huston]], [[Kendall Jenner]], [[Khloe Kardashian]], [[Jill Kelley]], [[Megyn Kelly]], [[Sarah Koenig]], [[Tara Lipinski]], [[Rachel Maddow]], [[Kate Middleton]], [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[Liza Minnelli]], [[Alanis Morissette]], [[Jeanine Pirro]], [[Michelle Rodriguez]], [[Melania Trump]], [[Ivana Trump]], [[Sofia Vergara]] and [[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://snlarchives.net/Cast/?CeSt|title=SNL Archives {{!}} Cast {{!}} Cecily Strong|website=snlarchives.net|access-date=2018-01-28}}</ref>
===Other work=== Strong was the featured entertainer at the 2015 [[White House Correspondents' Association]] dinner (cracking that she was the first straight woman to be so in twenty years).<ref>{{Citation|last=C-SPAN|title=Cecily Strong complete remarks at 2015 White House Correspondents' Dinner (C-SPAN)|date=April 25, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uH5XAeKdrjM|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> She took digs at the various news organizations in attendance, politicians of all persuasions, and [[President Obama]]. She also took shots at the [[US Secret Service]], host location the [[Washington Hilton]], [[Brian Williams]], [[Sarah Koenig]] and the state of [[Indiana]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/wp/2015/04/26/cecily-strongs-harshest-burns-in-her-white-house-correspondents-dinner-speech/ Cecily Strongâ€™s harshest burns in her White House correspondentsâ€™ dinner speech], ''[[Washington Post]]'', April 26, 2015. Retrieved May 1, 2015</ref>
In 2016, she appeared in a [[Television advertisement|commercial]] for [[Old Navy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.com/article/old-navy-enlists-snl-alums-improvise-series-online-spots/1393554|title=Old Navy enlists SNL alums to improvise series of online spots|publisher=Campaign Live|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> alongside other SNL cast members [[Nasim Pedrad]] and [[Jay Pharoah]]. That year, Strong also joined the climate change documentary show ''[[Years of Living Dangerously]]'' as a celebrity correspondent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/david-letterman-national-geographic-channel-climate-change-1201596066/|title=David Letterman Will Explore Climate Change For National Geographic Docu-Series|publisher=Variety|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, she guest starred as Samantha Stevens in [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]]'s ''[[Angie Tribeca]]'' and Catherine Hobart in [[FOX]]'s [[Scream Queens (2015 TV series)|''Scream Queens'']]. She appeared in a series of [[Television advertisement|commercials]] for [[Triscuit]] in 2017.
